    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-10-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-10-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="22"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Choate</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-10-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 15, 1904</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1453.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: * * * I have the honor to inclose the following
                    documents, viz:</p>
                <p>(1) The King’s proclamation of neutrality issued on February 11 last.<note n="a"
                        xml:id="d22fna">Printed in <ref target="frus1898#pg_862">Foreign Relations
                            1898, p. 862</ref>.</note> (2) Copy of a letter dated February 11 last,
                    addressed to the principal departments of His Majesty’s Government, informing
                    them of His Majesty’s resolution to maintain neutrality.<note n="b"
                        xml:id="d22fnb">Not printed. The proclamation and the letter of instruction
                        are expressed in the same terms as the proclamation of April 26, 1898, and
                        the letter of instruction of April 23, 1898, printed on <ref
                            target="frus1898#pg_865">pp. 865</ref> and <ref target="frus1898#pg_869"
                            >869, respectively, in Foreign Relations 1898</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">* * * * * * *</p>
                <p>I am, sir, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Joseph H. Choate.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
